rvelous sunshine.\"\nGeorge R. Marvin, Setana, Ala.:\n\"t wont fishlnf, caught a lot\nof fish and then enjoyed a good\nThanksgiving dinner at a local\nrestaurant.\"\nBenjamin Weiss, Yonkers, N.Y.:\n\"Wo just made it hero for\nmeg. aaHma am to/adwAe\nI nBfmuJTVHTjf I Fss^ fol TVMnWI*\nday afternoon. My family and I\nspent the day at the beach and\nraollv enUned U Ymaa Ul^a maa^A\nWjp uW w B^^F\nto be thankful for the fine\nweather you have.\"\nW.H. Williamson, Houston, Tex.:\n\"We took it easy and wore\nrealty thankful that we were kt\nnice warm Key West.\"\nConway West, Cleveland, Ohio:\n\"My son and I wont bridge\nfishing. Wo caught seme fish\n\u2022nd enjoyed the seonory at the\nFlorida Keys. Get some pretty\npood picture to show the folks\nback homo.\"\nMarcel Lanteau, Toronto, Caa.:\n\"We came south to escape the\n\u2022arty winter cold. Wo fourto tho\nright place. Sure, wo went swim.\nming and soaked up sun on Gio\nbeach.\"\nRosillo Dies At 81\nHAN ANA, Cuba Retired\nMaj. Domingo RosiHo, 31, who in\n1313 became the first Cuban to\nfly from Key West, Fla., to Ha\nvena, died at a mflitaT hospital\nhero toda^.\niKry West (Kittew\nHOTFR RMte\nDoctor Okays Ike\u2019s\nTrip To Gettysburg\nWASHINGTON (It President\nand 'Mrs. Eisenhower set out by\nautomobile today for a weekend\nor more at their Pennsylvania\nfarm In a striking new demonstra\ntion of bis speedy recovery from\na mild stroke.\nThe Pret nt, piling the move\non top of yesterday\u2019! burst of ac\ntivity which included surprise at\ntendance at a Thanksgiving\nchurch service, went wkh full ap\nproval from his doctors, the White\nHouse said.\nThe plan for the trip to Gettys\nburg, announced yesterday on a\n\u201chope* basis, was made firm\nearlier today on. the basis of a\nnew medical report of continued\n\u201cexcellent\" recovery progress.\n\"The doctors have agreed it is\nperfectly all right for him to make\nthe trip,\" press secretary James\nC. Hagerty said.\nThe presidential auto was fol\nlowed by a Secret Service car and\nanother White House limousine\ncarrying Maj.. Gen. Howard M,\nSnyder, White House physician,\nand some staff members.\nEisenhower had a long sleep,\nfrom g o'clock last night until 6\nthis morning, Hagerty said. It was\nnot that he was overly tired,\nHagerty said. He had a busy\nThanksgiving day, going to church\nand presiding over a family din\nner. Hagerty said Eisenhower re\ntired shortly after dinner.\nHow long they will remain is\nquestionable, but Hagerty said it\nwill be at least through the week\nend.\nHagerty said he probably will\nbe unable to announce anything\nm^re definite about the stay at\nthe farm until Sunday.\nA Cabinet meeting is scheduled\nMonday. And on Tuesday, con\ngressional leaders of both parties\nare coming to the White Hou^e\nfor a briefing on military and de\nfense matters and the legislative\nprogram tor the new congression\nal session.\nThere has been no change, Hag\nerty said, in plans for the session\nwLh congressional chiefs. But\nwhether Eisenhower personally\nwill sit m still is up in the air.\nHagerty read this brief 8:30\na.m. bulletin from the White\nHouse physician. Dr. Howard M.\nSnyder:\nThe President had a good\nnight's sleep. He slept almost con\ntinuously from early last evening\nwt il o'dock this morning. His\nprogress continues to be excel\nlent.\"\nWhile Hagerty was speaking\n\u00a9senhoner ass conferring with\nMs chief assistant. Shurman\nj Adams and Brig. Gen. Andruw\nTHE SOUTHERNMOST NEWSPAPER IN THE U.S.A.\nGood paster, White House staff\nsecretary, on official business.\nHagerty said that he and Dr.\nSnyder were the only White House\nofficials also making the trip to\nthe farm.\nThe new medical progress re\nport and the firming up of plans\nfor the Gettysburg run, together\nwith yesterday's surprise burst of\nactivity, added up to a signal of\na faster recovery pace than had\nbeen indicated by Eisenhower's\ndoctors.\nNixon May Sit In For Ike\nDecision Expected\nOn NATO Conclave\n1 By JOHN A. HARRIS\nWASHINGTON The White\nHouse may announce a decision\ni soon ap to whether Vice President\nNixon will ait in for the convalesc\n-1 ing President Eisenhower at the\nI NATO summit eonference in Paris\nnext month.\nNixon has said he is ready to\nigo, and apparently the NATO\n\u2018Council expects the vice president\nto attend the meeting which opens\nDec. 13.\nThe council said yesterday in a\nstatement released in Paris that\ni\u201cit learned with satisfaction that\n\u2018Viee President Nixon would lead\nthe American delegation.'*\nHowever, the final decision ap\nparently has not yet been made.\nIf Nixor. gets the assignment.\nhe would be catapulted into great\ner international prominence at a\ntime when his role as vice presi\ndent has taken on added signifi\ncance at home.\nHe has spent many hours at\nthe White House since Eisenhower\nwas stricken Monday with a\nblockage of a small brain artery.\nNixon has maintained througb\nout that he was not assuming any\npresidential duties, and has said\nhe expects Eisenhower to be back\non the job after a short period of\nconvalescence.\nNixon stood in for Eisenhower\n'yesterday in bidding farewell at\nthe airport to King Mohammed V\nof Morocco, who was leaving aft.\ner three days of talks with U. S.\nofficials.\nWhen be stopped by at the\nWhite House later, Nixon said he\nplanned to meet with Sherman\nAdams. Eisenhower\u2019s top aide.\nNixon added the purpose of his\nj visit was to \"see whether there\nare any loose ends that I can take\n.care of.\"\nKEY WEST, FLORIDA. FRIDAY, NOVEMBER \u201eJ7\nThe White House continues to\nemphasize that the road to com\nplete recovery still stretches a\ngood distance into the future. His\nI physicians are pictured as believ\ning Eisenhower must have sever\nal weeks of rest before he can\nreturn to his job full time-\ni Elsenhower spent half an hour\nwith Adams and Goodpaster,\nsigned 11 papers and initialed an\nother, Hagerty said.\nThe President received his aides\n(Continued on Page Four)\nIt was at the airport that Nixon,\nin response to queries from news\nmen. indicated his willingness to\ngo to the Paris NATO conference.\n\"I am always ready to do what\never President Eisenhower wants\nme to,\u201d he said.\nNixon added that the question\nas to \u201cwho wou'd make up the\nUnited States delegation\" will be\nsubmitted to Eisenhower.\nThe White House said Eisenhow\ner's doctors will decide later\ni whether he is up to making the\ntrip.\nNixon held his first news con-\nI ference at the White House\nWednesday.\nHe said he was not doing any\nmore than he did in 1955 when\nEisenhower suffered a heart at\ntack.\nHe said Eisenhower asked him\nthis week to sec that meetings of\nthe Cabinet and National Security\nCouncil are held on schedule dur\ning Eisenhower's absence. Nixon\nwill preside at the sessions as he\ndid in 1955.\nMay Be Off 1,000 In Year, Experts Estimate\nHighway Toll Drops In U.S. p\nCHICAGO JF The 1957 death\ntoll on the nation's highways\nmight be 1.000 less than last year.,\nthe National Safety Council esti-i\nmated today.\nCouncil officials said their opti\nmistic estimate of 38.600 deaths\nwas based on three factors:\n1. Some 31,350 highway deaths:\nduring the first in months, about j\n800 Jess than 1856.\n2. During the first eight months\u00ab\nRocket Of U.S. Satellite\nLaunching T o Be Visible\nMartin Co.\nContinues\nDec. 4 Plan\nBALTIMORE (AP)\n\u2014The tiny test satellite the\nUnited States hopes to\nlaunch Dec. 4 will not be\nvisible to the naked eye,\nbutj its five n fbotu- long\nbrijthtlypAihtedihird-stage\nMiiHlHeFw^uW^\nsatel-\nbeen\nfe\u00bbM <H\u00bbsW\u2018Wi 4MB\nRiW W *?8 2* 8#\n^lt pod r^el.^jM\nfl We&At IR iPMHPfW\npoewi 4Rse^..mpqnto4,on,Xhe\nRwihiosl. ,p|ipi e mamiiM oti Hie\n1 Ohly the nose of the rocket,\nwhich will be completely cloaked\nin aa apron of the bigger second\nstage rocket, is shown in the\nphotograph. But it reveals a while\nspherical shape, about 12 to 15 in\nches across, on which the tiny\nsatellite Is mounted.\nAfter about 40 miles of ascent,\nthe seven-toot-lqng asbestbs-pias\ndc nose cone of the rocket will i\nip tow and fall off, leg tog\ntie satellite exposed lor the rest\nof its climb.\nThe jiose cone wilt protect the\nsatellite from aerodynamic heat\ning expected to reach 1.500 de\ngrees Fahrenheit through the\nearth's dense lower atmosphere.\nThe photograph also shows lour\nrods which brace the satellite to\nthe walls of the second-stage rock\net apron.\nAt about 287 miles, just short\nof orbital altitude, a spin table,\npropelled by tiny jets, will start\nth r entire third stage with Ls still\nattached satellite rotating. After\nthe first complete spin, the sup\nporting rods will snap out of the\nwaj and leave the shiny alumi\nnum sphere ready for its spring\ninto space.\nRebel-Set Fires\nDestroy Cuban\nSugar Cane Crops\nHAVANA, Cuba UT\u2014 Fires were\nreported sweeping over a wide\narea of sugar cane fields last\nnight in southeast Cuba\u2014set by\nrebels trying to bring down the\n'government by ruining the sugar\ncrop and causing economic hard\nship.\nThe fires were reported in Ori\nente province, center of rebels led\nby Fidel Castro, who launched\nthe fire offensive several weeks\nago. Sugar industry spokesmen in\nHavana predicted that the burn\ning would fail to ruin Cuba's main\nexport crop.\nMeanwhile, there were new but\nunconfirmed rumors that reinforce\nments for Castro have landed\nfrom Florida and Mexico.\nBang-Up Reunion\nDES MOINES (AP) When\nthe automobiles of Ardith Kay\nThomas, 21. of lowa City, and\nWilliam Toerber, 79. of Lowden.\ncollided near Clarence, neighbors\ncalled it a family get together.\nArdith is Toerber's niece.\nof 1957, 5.6 persons died for every\n100 million miles of highway trav- 1\nel. Last year, the figure was 6.\n3. Twenty-nine of 46 states re\nporting showed traffic records for\nthe first 10 months of 1957 which\nwere unproved over last year.!\nMontana and Idaho showed 29 per\ncent improvements.\nIn October, 455 of the reporting\ncities had perfect records. The\ni throe largest were Richmond, Va. i\nw 1 I\nwSf\"*\nGlCMApdf D WlT^MU|R.\u00ablt\u2014Army man Grogor^LKupslci, 23, loft, sits besido dsfents counsel\nCapt. Jarnos K. Robinson of Yokohama, Japan, today. Kupski is charged with killing Kasuo lb\nkawa, 2S-year>eld Jap gir\\ Caso may result In another jurisdictional dispute between Japs and U.S,\n\u2014AP Wirepheto. E.\nGl Charge^ If Strangulation\nAccused Strangler\nFaces Mental Probe\nBy DAVID LANCASHIRE\nYOKOHAMA, Japan Oft Spe\ncialist Gregory J. Kupski of De\ntroit, charged by the U. S. Army\nwith the strrngulation murder of\na Japanese girl, is under military\npsychiatric examination, his de\nfense counsel sa.M today. i\nThe counsel, Capt. James R.\nRobinson, 34, Ft. Collins, Colo.,\nParents, Kids Found Roaming Streets\nGhost Gets Blamed\nFor Family Trouble\nSUNDERLAND. England Uft\nMr. and Mrs. Norman Dixon say\ntheir happy family was broken up\nby a ghost.\nThe Dixons, arrested on a\ncharge of neglecting their three\nchildren, told a court the ghost\ninvaded their home in a city\nbousing development last March.\n\"We saw a shimmering coil on\nthe wall.\u201d Norman. 27. said. \"We\nheard footsteps on the stairs when\nthere was nobody there. At night\ncold hands pulled off the bed\nclothes and clutched us.\"\nThe Dixons finally called in the\nRt. Rev. John Ramsbotham. bish\nop of Jarrow. who tried to exor\ncis. the specter by walking\nthrough the house in his robe and\nmitre and carrying h?s staff. The\nghost refused to cooperate.\nJacksonville, Fla., and Salt Lake\nCity. Utah. I\u2019\nThere were 135 cities which had\nperfect records during the first\n10 months. The three largest were\nLynn. Mass.. Rock Island, 111.,:\nand Ann Arbor, Mieh.\nIn 1956, 33,623 died ia highway!\naccidents.\nThe council said deaths in Oc\nitober totaled 3,480, approximately\nIthe same as in October 1356.\ni which was Um lowest since 134\u00ae.\nf would not elaborate on the dis\nclosure.\nRobinson spoke at a 20-minute\nnews conference. The 23-year-old\nsoldier, -who the Army says has\nconfessed the crime, was at his\nside, neatly attired in a freshly\npressed uniform.\n\u201cI can't speak too much Japa\nnese,\u201d were the only w'ords Kup-\n\"I asked the Council for an ex\nchange of houses.\" Dixon said. \"I\nwas told I could try to arrange\na private exchange, but when peo\nple learned our house was haunt\ned they -wouldn't trade.\u201d\nIn an effort to force the City\nCouncil's hand, Dixon said, he de\ncided to quit paying the rent.\nThe Council merely evicted the\nDixons from the house.\nPolice witnesses said they found\nthe young father and mother and\ntheir three sons, ranging from 18\nmonths to 4 years, wandering\naround in the rain.\nThe court put the Dixons on\nprobation for 12 months. \u201cYou\natied stupidly.\" the judge said.\n\"?n leaving the bouse without\nmaking proper arrangements for\nyour children.\"\nMr. and Mrs. Dixon are staying\na\u00bb the home of his bro:her. The\nchildren are at a city child center.\nThe haunted house is still\nempty.\nStudents Riot After\nEdison-Miami Game\nMIAMI. Fla. (fl Roiling stu-;\ndents and police clashed early to\nday in the aftermath o' Edison!\nHigh School\u2019s 20-7 football vktory\nover Miami High.\nSeveral police, one fireman and\n\u2022ome students were reported in\njured by clubs, fists, bottles or\nrocks.\nOfficers turned a fire hose on\nthe fkanoaatrators and students;\natop roofs of nearby stores hurled I*\natones and batleu at th^police. j\nWeather Summary\nClear to partly cloudy. Possi\nbility of scattered showers. Low\ntonight. 78. High Saturday, near\n83. Tomorrow's tides: High. 4:23\na. m., 5:04 p. m. Low, 10:11 a. m.,\n11:20 p. m.\nFRICK FIVB Cl NTS\nski said in answer to barrage\nof questions.\nKupati has been charged \"with\nunpremeditated murder' in the\ndeath of Kazue Eikawa, 25, whose\nnude body was found in a Yoko\nhama alley Nov. 17. The charge\ncarries a maximum Army penalty\nof life imprisonment.\nNo clue to whether Japan er the\nUnited States will take jurisdic\ntion was given. Robinson said,\n\"The decision lies with the gov\nernments concerned.\u201d Both be\nand Kupski feel either nation\nwould provide a fair trial, he add\ned. The maximum Japanese pen\nalty is death.\nRobinson said the Army has\ngranted permission- for Kupski to\nre-enact the crime for Japanese\npolice, but said he did not know\nIf this will be done.\nThe case has attracted atten\ntion here becaus it posed a poe\nsible jurisdictional dispute ha\ntweer. Japan and the United States\nin the wake of the internationally\ncontested Girard firing range\nshooting.\nThe Yokohama procurator's of\nfice is still investigating but has\nnot issued an indictment The^e\nare indications the Army will ro\nlinquMi jurisdiction if it does.\nThe dead girl was the wife of\nRobert Leslie Wescot. a V. JL\nNavy man now stationed at China\nLake Naval Base in Calitornig,\nRobinson said Kupski was con\nvicted of petty larceny by *e\nArmy in April 193\u00ab and demoted\nfrom Pfc. to private. He has no\nother civilian or military convic\ntions. Robinson sa\u00bbd.\nBoth Kupski and Robinson re\nfused to say how long the soldier\nhad known the murdered gH.\nwgkt WfW* sKS\nIw Wws wJ\ni J\u00aeW\nIm*","height":"26118","width":"19620"}}
